Scallops 101: If you love ordering scallops at restaurants, but are intimidated about cooking them at home, here are my tips for making sure they come out perfect every time! 
.
.
.
1. Pat the scallops with a paper towel to make sure they are completely dry before cooking. Any moisture will inhibit them from getting a nice golden brown crust.
2. Season generously with salt, but hold off on adding any other seasonings in the beginning to ensure they don’t burn in the pan. You can add more flavor once you’ve gotten a good sear on the scallops. 
3. Use a non-stick pan and make sure it’s smoking hot before adding in your oil. 
4. Once you add the scallops to the pan, don’t disturb them for 2-3 minutes. If the scallops are sticking to the pan, they’re not done! They’ll release from the pan on their own when they’re ready.
5. Once you flip the scallops, lower the heat to low and add butter and any other flavorings you like - garlic, fresh herbs, spices, etc. Baste the scallops with the butter for another minute, then remove from the heat and serve with your favorite sauces or sides. Perfect scallops every time!

12 Days of Cooking Basics! A new series to help you master all the quintessential skills of cooking before ushering in the new year! Day 1 - The perfect boiled egg 🥚

1. Fill a small saucepan with water (there should be enough water that your eggs are fully submerged once you put them in).
2. Bring the water to a full boil.
3. Once your water is boiling, gently place your eggs in the saucepan. If you let them fall into the pan, they will crack and your eggs will break. 
4. Depending on your preference, pull your eggs out at exactly 6 min, 8 min, and/or 10 min.
5. Submerge the eggs in a bowl of ice water to stop them from cooking further.
6. Peel and serve! 

6 min eggs: completely runny yolk - these are perfect in ramen, over rice, etc.

8 min eggs: soft-boiled, half-set yolks - these are great over buttered toast or in sandwiches.

10 min eggs: hardboiled, completely set yolks - use these for egg salad, potato salad, deviled eggs, etc.

My Egg Salad Recipe:
1. Mash 1 10-min hard-boiled egg in a small bowl.
2. To the bowl, add 1 tsp finely chopped Serrano chili (optional), 1 tbsp thinly sliced green onion, 2 tbsp mayo, and 1/4 tsp salt & black pepper (season to taste and add more salt/pepper if you’d like). Mix everything together.
3. Slice an 8-min egg lengthwise and place half of it, yolk-side down, on a piece of toast (I’m using Japanese milk bread, but any soft white bread will do).
4. Add the egg salad mixture on top, then top with another slice of bread. 
5. Cut the sandwich in half (in the same direction as the egg) with a sharp knife.

12 Days of Cooking Basics! A series to help you master all the quintessential skills of cooking before ushering in the new year! Day 2 - Homemade Broth 🍜 Once you’ve mastered an easy homemade broth, the opportunities for different types of soups/stews are endless.

1. Use a big pot-this broth takes hours to cook and it refrigerates and freezes well, so it’s in your best interest to make a large batch.
2. If you are making a meat broth, the first thing you want to do is brown your meat. Whether you’re using chicken, turkey, beef, etc., browning the meat first in some oil will give your broth extra flavor. You can use bone-in or boneless meat - bone-in will give more flavor to your broth, but if you prefer boneless, that’s fine too!
3. The next step is to add all of your veggies. This broth is a great way to use up all the veggies in your fridge before they go bad. You can use fresh or frozen, and the more you use the better! There is no specific combination of veggies-onions, carrots, celery, scallions, leeks, garlic, ginger, etc. 
4. Once your veggies have been added to the pan, add enough water to cover everything.
5. Now the seasonings-salt obviously, but everything else is up to your preference! I typically add some turmeric for the health benefits, black pepper, and some chicken buillion for added flavor. You can also use paprika, garlic powder, ground ginger, garlic, star anise, bay leaves, dried herbs (add fresh herbs at the end).
6. Bring the broth to a boil, then cover and let it cook on low heat as as long as you possibly can. You’ll know it’s ready if the meat is tender (if you’re using meat), and the veggies have softened. Cooking longer=more flavor. 
7. Taste your broth! Season to taste with more fresh herbs and spices. More salt will help bring out the flavors in your soup, so if it tastes bland, add more salt.
8. Once it’s ready, strain the broth, let it cool completely, pour into containers, and refrigerate or freeze until you need it!
9. The broth can be served as is, or eaten with fresh cooked noodles and your favorite toppings, or used in soups/stews/gravies/etc.

12 Days of Cooking Basics! A series to help you master all the quintessential skills of cooking before ushering in the new year! Day 3 - Pickling. Pickling, the process of preserving foods in an acidic solution, plays an important role in the diet of many cultures around the world. Using vinegar is the easiest, quickest, and least intimidating way to pickle something. 

This ‘recipe’ for picked veggies is super versatile, and you can swap out different ingredients to match whatever you already have in your pantry.

1. In an airtight container, mix together 1 cup water, 1/2 vinegar, 1 tbsp sugar, and 1 1/2 tsp kosher salt. Make sure the sugar and salt are dissolved in the liquid. 
2. Add sliced veggies and 1/2 tsp of any additional seasonings (optional)
3. Place in the refrigerator for at least an hour so the veggies can marinade and soften.
4. You can then either drain the veggies and serve them how you’d like or you can let them sit in the pickling liquid for up to two weeks in the refrigerator.

Variations:
Veggies - onions, carrots, cucumbers, cauliflower, peppers, radishes 
Vinegar- white vinegar, apple cider vinegar, red wine vinegar, rice vinegar
Sweetener- sugar, maple syrup, honey
Seasonings - black peppercorns, coriander, red pepper flakes, fresh herbs, garlic cloves 

As long as you stick to the general ratios of water, vinegar, salt, and sweetener above, you can’t go wrong! 

Pickled onions are so easy to things to make (I used a combination of red and white onions, + black peppercorns and garlic cloves for flavor), but they add a delicious punch to whatever you put them on. A few of my favorite ways to enjoy pickled onions:

- On top of scrambled eggs or avo toast for breakfast
- Added to your favorite sandwich 
- Scattered on top of rice and grain bowls 
- Mixed into a salad 
- As a taco condiment 
- Eaten as a side with grilled or bbq’d meats

12 Days of Cooking Basics! A series to help you master all the quintessential skills of cooking before ushering in the new year! Day 4 - Steamed Rice 🍚. Never mess up white rice at home again! Here are a few easy steps to make perfect fluffy rice on a stove (no rice cooker needed). 

1. Add rice to a bowl and rinse with cold water. This helps to remove impurities and extra starch on the surface of the rice, which can make the rice gummy. Rub the rice between your fingers to remove as much starch as possible-the water gets cloudy when you do this.  Rinse and drain the water at least 2-3 times until your water is clear. 
2. Soak the rice in water for at least 15 minutes. This is optional, but I find that this helps to make the rice fluffy and reduces cooking time! It’s also been found that soaking rice helps to breakdown compounds in the rice that make it easier to digest.
3. Measure your rice and water! For most types of rice, the ratio of water to rice should be 2:1. I’m using 1.5 cups of Basmati rice, so I need 3 cups of water. 
4. Combine the rice and water in a pot, turn the heat to high, and wait for it to boil. 
5. Once the rice is boiling and has started floating or dancing at the top of the water, turn the heat to low and cover with a lid. 
6. Let the rice steam for 15 minutes. Do not remove the lid during this time otherwise all of your steam will escape. (Keep in mind that different types of rice cook for different times). Having a glass lid on your pot can be helpful! Once all of the water has evaporated; your rice is ready! 

Variations:
- Instead of water, use vegetable or chicken broth to add flavor
- Add dry seasoning to the water before you cook your rice, such as cumin, paprika, turmeric, etc. 
- Stir in fresh herbs after the rice has cooked, such as dill or cilantro 
- Melt some butter in the pan (and sauté any seasonings) before adding the rice and water to add more richness

12 Days of Cooking Basics! A series to help you master all the quintessential skills of cooking before ushering in the new year! Day 5 - Candied Nuts 🥜. Candied Nuts are a holiday classic, but they’re so easy to make, you can enjoy them all year round in lots of different ways. These candied nuts will instantly elevate your cooking skills and impress everyone around you. They can be served as a cocktail snack, a garnish over salads and roasted veggies (I love candied pecans over a beet salad), or on top of your favorite desserts (over ice cream or sprinkled on bread pudding). 

Recipe:
1. Line a cooking/baking sheet with parchment paper. 
2. In a nonstick skillet on medium-high heat, combine 1 cup sugar, 1/2 cup water, 2 tbsp butter, 2 tsp vanilla, and 1 tsp cinnamon. 
3. Bring the mixture to a boil, then add in 14oz of nuts.
4. Stir constantly. The mixture will go from a thin liquid to a thick coating around the nuts in about 10 minutes. 
5. Immediately pour the nuts out onto your cookie sheet and spread them out in an even layer. 
6. Once the nuts are completely cool, break them apart and store in an airtight container (up to 2 weeks at room temp) until you’re ready to serve! 

Variations:
- You can use Almonds, Pecans, Cashews, Walnuts, or a combination- just use raw nuts, not roasted or salted
- Add a pinch of cayenne to make spicy/sweet nuts, or cardamom/nutmeg for a warm holiday version
- Replace some of the sugar with maple syrup for a rich, maple flavor 
- Zest some orange or lemon zest over the nuts to give them a citrus flavor 
- Drizzle some melted chocolate over the nuts after they have cooled

12 Days of Cooking Basics! A series to help you master all the quintessential skills of cooking before ushering in the new year! Day 6 - the Classic French Omelet. Unlike American-style omelets, French Omelets are cooked quickly so the outside is smooth and golden and the inside is custardy. Mastering a French omelet is what some consider the greatest test of a new cook in the kitchen :)

Recipe:
1. In a small nonstick pan on medium heat, melt 1 tbsp of butter.
2. As soon as the butter has melted and starts to foam (we don’t want it to brown), add 2 beaten eggs. The eggs should be beaten just until no white remains - we don’t want to mix too much and incorporate any air into the eggs. 
3. Use a rubber spatula to stir the eggs quickly until the mixture just starts to form curds. Then spread the eggs evenly on the bottom of the pan, covering up any gaps.
4. Turn the heat to low, and after about 15 seconds, start to roll the omelet a little at a time with your spatula. Roll the egg away from yourself so it ends up at the end of the pan. 
5. Turn the omelet out onto a plate with the  seam-side down. Rub the top with softened butter (this gives it a glossy finish that French omelets are known for) and season with salt and fresh herbs. 

Variations:
A classic French omelet never has anything but fresh herbs and/or cheese, but here are a couple of options:
- Herbs: chives, scallions, tarragon. These can be added before cooking, or sprinkled over the top of the omelet 
- Cheese: Add grated cheese (such as mozzarella, gruyère, Parmesan) or a soft cheese (goat cheese, Boursin, cream cheese) to the center of the omelet right before you start rolling. 

Practice makes perfect when it comes to the French Omelet, so don’t give up if it doesn’t come out perfect the first time!

12 Days of Cooking Basics! A series to help you master all the quintessential skills of cooking before ushering in the new year! Day 7 - Fudge 🍫. Every home cook should have at least one dessert recipe in their arsenal. Fudge is the easiest, most versatile no-bake dessert you can serve at home or gift to friends! You need just three simple ingredients to make fudge - butter, sweetened condensed milk, and chocolate chips - but the recipe variations are endless! This recipe makes the perfect hostess/holiday gift because it travels well and keeps perfectly well at room temp for at least 1 week! 

Base Ingredients:
1. 3 cups chocolate chips - white, milk, semi-sweet, dark
2. 1 14oz can sweetened condensed milk 
3. 3 tbsp butter 

Steps:
1. Line any sized dish (8x8 or 9x13 works best) with parchment paper.
2. Add chocolate chips, condensed milk, and butter to a saucepan. Stir constantly on medium-low heat until the mixture is fully melted and smooth. Then remove from the heat.
3. Add any mix-ins. I’m using crushed Oreos, but you can add anything you like (some ideas below!)
4. Spread the mixture into your pan in an even layer and refrigerate until fully set. Then cut into small pieces. 

Variations:
1. Cookies & cream - white chocolate with 2 cups crushed Oreos 
2. Cranberry & pistachio - white chocolate with 1/2 cup dried cranberries and 1/2 cup chopped pistachios 
3. Rocky Road - semi-sweet chocolate with 1/2 cup each walnuts and marshmallows 
4. Birthday cake - white chocolate with 1/2 cup sprinkles mixed in and added on top
